<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    Demo Case 10 - Closed / Complaint / Critical priority
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the LAST and FINAL of the 10-case demo dataset; together
    with cases 01 through 09 it satisfies the AAP requirement (Section
    0.7.4) of "at least 10 demo cases across all six statuses and both
    case types," and completes the dataset matrix:

        Case 01 - Draft       / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 02 - Open        / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 03 - In Progress / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 04 - Pending     / General Inquiry / Low
        Case 05 - Resolved    / General Inquiry / High
        Case 06 - Closed      / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 07 - Open        / Complaint       / High
        Case 08 - In Progress / Complaint       / Critical
        Case 09 - Resolved    / Complaint       / High
        Case 10 - Closed      / Complaint       / Critical   ## THIS FILE

    The 10-case dataset thus exercises:
      * Every one of the six statuses (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed)
      * Both case types (General Inquiry and Complaint) across the
        full lifecycle
      * All four priorities (Low, Medium, High, Critical) - this case
        is the SECOND of two Critical-priority cases (the other is
        case 08), ensuring the all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar
        chart has a non-empty Critical bar with diverse statuses

    Role / cross-dependency context (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This case DEPENDS ON (loaded BEFORE this record):
        - The scoped application records under ../../app/
            (sys_app and sys_scope; this case's <sys_scope>/<sys_package>
             reference fields resolve via the source attribute against
             those records)
        - The case table definition at ../../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml
            (this record's <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case</sys_class_name>
             requires the table to exist)
        - All dictionary entries for the case table under
            ../../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_*.xml  (every populated
            field below requires its dictionary entry to be present)
        - All choice records under ../../choices/  (the type=Complaint,
            status=Closed, and priority=Critical choice values must be
            registered)
        - The auto-numbering record at
            ../../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case.xml  (defines the
            CASE0000001 format; this record's <number/> is intentionally
            empty so the platform auto-generates per that format on
            insert)
        - The role records under ../../roles/  (the
            block_terminal_closed business rule will reference the
            x_[scope]_case_manager role; the demo agent's read access
            requires the x_[scope]_case_agent role and its ACLs)
        - The ACL records under ../../acl/  (table-level and field-level
            ACLs gate read/write access; the Closed status row is
            read-only to all roles via the block_terminal_closed
            business rule)
        - The business rule records under ../../business_rules/
            (block_terminal_closed will fire on subsequent updates;
            set_closed_date and set_opened_date are bypassed at insert
            time for this Closed-on-insert case, requiring the explicit
            date overrides below)
        - ../users/sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml  (referenced by
            <assigned_agent>; resolved by user_name lookup)
        - ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml  (referenced
            by <assigned_group>; resolved by name lookup)
        - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
            (grants the case_agent role to the demo agent so the agent
            can read this case via the "Assigned only" ACL clause)

      This case IS REFERENCED BY (loaded AFTER this record):
        - NONE under ../tasks/  (closed cases have no demo tasks; the
            seed-script's task table includes tasks ONLY on cases 03,
            04, 05, 08, 09)
        - NONE under ../parties/  (closed cases have no demo parties;
            the seed-script's party table includes parties ONLY on
            cases 03, 04, 05, 08, 09)
        - The avg_time_to_close Manager View dashboard widget at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml
            (THIS CASE IS ONE OF EXACTLY TWO INPUTS: case 06 contributes
             a ~18-day duration and case 10 contributes a ~14-day
             duration; together they yield a meaningful average of
             approximately 16 days for the AVG widget. Without case 10,
             the average would degenerate to a single-sample constant
             of case 06's duration.)
        - The all_cases_by_status Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status.xml  (this case
            populates the Closed bar)
        - The all_cases_by_type Manager View donut at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml  (this case
            populates the Complaint slice)
        - The all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority.xml  (THIS
            CASE PROVIDES ONE OF THE TWO CRITICAL ENTRIES; the other is
            case 08)
        - The cases_opened_30d Manager View single-score widget at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml  (with
            opened_date approximately 15 days ago, this case is included
            in the count of cases opened within the last 30 days)
        - The block_terminal_closed business rule test in Validation
            Gate 2: this case is the canonical test record verifying
            the rule applies to Complaint-type cases (not just General
            Inquiry); attempting to update ANY field on this case must
            surface the verbatim error "Closed cases are terminal and
            cannot be modified." (per AAP Section 0.5.5)

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's ten authoring rules):

      Rule 1 - Synthetic only:
        subject       = "Demo case 10: Closed (Complaint)"
        description   = "Synthetic Closed complaint case - completed
                         lifecycle." (no PII; the dash separator avoids
                         any em-dash or special characters that could
                         trip XML parsing)
        requester_name  = "Synthetic Requester Ten" (synthetic identifier
                          using the literal word "Synthetic" plus a
                          numeral spelled out for the requester, NOT a
                          real person's name)
        requester_email = "requester-10@example.invalid"
                          (RFC 2606 / BCP 32 reserved .invalid TLD never
                          resolves to a real domain; the local part uses
                          the NUMERAL "10" matching the file numbering,
                          NOT the spelled-out word "ten" - this is a
                          deliberate design choice consistent with the
                          file's idempotent file-name convention)

      Rule 2 - No auto-number override:
        The <number/> element is intentionally absent. The auto-number
        engine defined in ../../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case.xml
        generates a CASE0000001-format value on insert per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (the "number" row of the case schema specifies "Auto-
        number" with format CASE0000001 and Read-only constraint).

      Rule 3 - Explicit date overrides (CRITICAL FOR THIS CASE):
        opened_date = "2026-04-15 09:00:00"
            (computed at file generation time as today UTC minus 15 days
             at 09:00:00; the value is fixed at generation time, NOT
             evaluated at import time, because Update Set XML is a
             static document)
        closed_date = "2026-04-29 17:00:00"
            (computed at file generation time as today UTC minus 1 day
             at 17:00:00)
        Duration = approximately 14 days, 8 hours
            (the small intra-day fraction does not change the AVG
             materially; the widget rounds to days)

        WHY both fields are explicit XML values and not left to the
        business rules:
          * The set_opened_date Before-Insert business rule sets
            opened_date = gs.nowDateTime() at insert time, which would
            yield a value ~15 days AFTER the desired opened_date.
          * The set_closed_date Before-Update business rule fires only
            on Resolved -> Closed transition, NOT on direct insert with
            status = Closed. So closed_date would remain null on insert.
          * Without explicit XML values both date fields would be wrong:
            opened_date would equal "now" (giving zero duration) and
            closed_date would be null (giving NULL duration, which the
            avg_time_to_close report excludes).
          * Therefore the agent prompt mandates explicit overrides.

        WHY the duration differs from case 06 (~18 days):
          The avg_time_to_close widget computes
            AVG(closed_date - opened_date) over Closed cases.
          With only one Closed case the AVG is a constant; with two
          Closed cases having identical durations the AVG is still a
          constant. To make the widget output meaningful and to mimic
          real-world variation, case 06 has a (~20 days, ~2 days)
          opened/closed profile = ~18 days, while case 10 has a
          (~15 days, ~1 day) profile = ~14 days. The two-sample
          average is approximately 16 days, demonstrating that the
          dashboard correctly aggregates across multiple cases.

      Rule 4 - Both assignments populated, NO pending_reason:
        assigned_group = "x_[scope]_demo_team"  (mandatory because the
                         case had to traverse Open -> ... -> Closed,
                         and assigned_group is required at Open per
                         AAP Section 0.5.5; the value persists through
                         all subsequent statuses)
        assigned_agent = "x_[scope]_demo_agent"  (mandatory because the
                         case had to traverse In Progress -> ... ->
                         Closed, and assigned_agent is required at In
                         Progress per AAP Section 0.5.5; the value
                         persists)
        pending_reason = (absent / unpopulated)  (Closed cases never
                         carry a pending_reason; if the case ever
                         transitioned through Pending, the
                         clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress business
                         rule would have cleared the value when the
                         case left Pending)

      Rule 5 - Choice value precision:
        type     = "Complaint"  (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml; the second
                   of the two case types)
        status   = "Closed"     (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml; the
                   terminal state; capital C deliberate - "Closed"
                   not "closed" or "CLOSED")
        priority = "Critical"   (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml; the
                   highest priority; capital C deliberate - "Critical"
                   not "critical" or "CRITICAL")
        Note: "Closed" and "Critical" both begin with capital C; this
        co-occurrence is intentional and exercises the dataset's
        priority-status orthogonality.

      Rule 6 - Zero hardcoded sys_id cross-references:
        The case's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key,
        which is acceptable per the AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to
        any other record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase
        hex value computed at file generation time as the MD5 of the
        idempotent subject "Demo case 10: Closed (Complaint)" =
        3e950cc7aa88d253150b9b1b5edce3c5 - so the Update Set engine
        resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import, making the record
        idempotent.

        EVERY cross-reference field below uses the stable human-readable
        lookup key (user_name / name / scope source) as both the
        display_value attribute AND the text content - NOT a hardcoded
        sys_id literal. This matches the convention established by every
        peer file in the scoped Update Set (sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, dictionary/x_[scope]_*, etc.) and complies
        with the AAP Section 0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals anywhere" rule:
          - <assigned_agent display_value="x_[scope]_demo_agent">
                x_[scope]_demo_agent
            </assigned_agent>  resolves by user_name lookup
          - <assigned_group display_value="x_[scope]_demo_team">
                x_[scope]_demo_team
            </assigned_group>  resolves by name lookup
          - <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
                resolves by scope source-name lookup
          - <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">
                x_[scope]
            </sys_package>  resolves by scope source-name lookup

      Rule 7 - Scope binding:
        <sys_scope>   binds this case row to the scoped application via
                      the scope source name "x_[scope]" defined in
                      ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml at
                      <source>x_[scope]</source>; the display_value
                      "Case Management" matches the sys_app's human-
                      readable name.
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the additional
                      source="x_[scope]" attribute that is required by
                      the Update Set engine for scope-package binding.
        Note: the source attribute value "x_[scope]" matches what every
        peer file uses; it is the scope's <source> field, NOT the
        scoped application's sys_update_name. This is the convention
        used consistently across the project's Update Set artifacts.

      Rule 8 - Idempotency anchor:
        The case's idempotent key is <subject> =
        "Demo case 10: Closed (Complaint)". The companion seed script
        ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js ensureCase() helper queries
        x_[scope]_case by subject BEFORE inserting; the
        action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner <x_[scope]_case>
        element ensures the same behavior at Update Set import time.
        Both the action attribute and the deterministic sys_id make
        re-imports on a fresh PDI byte-identical and collision-free.

      Rule 9 - Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element:  <record_update table="x_[scope]_case">
        Inner element: <x_[scope]_case action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
                       idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1
                       round-trip-verification gate (Validation Gate 7).
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the established peer
        convention used by sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, role records, and dictionary entries
        across the scoped Update Set).

      Rule 10 - Date format strictness:
        ServiceNow's GlideDateTime parses string dates in the format
        "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS" using the instance default time zone (or
        UTC for system-level imports). The two date values below use:
          * 24-hour, zero-padded time (09:00:00 not 9:00:00 AM)
          * No timezone suffix (no Z, no offset; the import treats the
            value as UTC for the system timezone)
          * Hyphen-separated date (2026-04-15 not 2026/04/15)
          * Single-space date/time separator (not 'T')
        These conventions match the GlideDateTime.setDisplayValue()
        contract documented for ServiceNow scoped applications.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        ArkCase's CaseFile JPA entity declares ~80 fields including a
        terminal "DRAFT" default status with a queue-handler-driven
        transition to "ACTIVE" on save, plus a polymorphic disposition
        sub-entity capturing close metadata. The ServiceNow target
        collapses this to the user-prompt's 12-field schema
        (number, type, status, priority, subject, description,
        opened_date, closed_date, assigned_group, assigned_agent,
        requester_name, requester_email - plus the optional
        pending_reason). ArkCase's Disposition.java entity captures
        closeDate and dispositionType for case closure metadata; the
        ServiceNow target uses only closed_date.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag)
        returns zero errors.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches against (john|jane|smith|doe|
        @gmail|@yahoo|@outlook|@hotmail|\.com|\.org|\.net) - the
        synthetic identifiers ("Synthetic Requester Ten",
        "requester-10@example.invalid", "x_[scope]_demo_agent",
        "x_[scope]_demo_team") do not include any PII tokens.
      - Date validation grep:
          grep -E '<(opened|closed)_date>[0-9]{4}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{2}
                   [0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}:[0-9]{2}</(opened|closed)_date>'
        returns exactly 2 matches (both date fields populated with
        valid YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS values).
      - Numeral validation grep:
          grep -E 'requester-10@example\.invalid'
        returns exactly 1 match (verifying the numeral "10", not the
        word "ten").
      - Choice-value validation: <type>Complaint</type>,
        <status>Closed</status>, <priority>Critical</priority> -
        capital C in both Closed and Critical.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim in the
        sys_class_name, sys_update_name, all reference values, and the
        file path; the PDI auto-assigns the actual concrete scope id at
        App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-time
        substitution propagates consistently across all bracketed
        placeholders.
-->
<record_update table="x_[scope]_case">
    <x_[scope]_case action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <assigned_agent display_value="x_[scope]_demo_agent">x_[scope]_demo_agent</assigned_agent>
        <assigned_group display_value="x_[scope]_demo_team">x_[scope]_demo_team</assigned_group>
        <closed_date>2026-04-29 17:00:00</closed_date>
        <description>Synthetic Closed complaint case - completed lifecycle.</description>
        <opened_date>2026-04-15 09:00:00</opened_date>
        <priority>Critical</priority>
        <requester_email>requester-10@example.invalid</requester_email>
        <requester_name>Synthetic Requester Ten</requester_name>
        <status>Closed</status>
        <subject>Demo case 10: Closed (Complaint)</subject>
        <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>3e950cc7aa88d253150b9b1b5edce3c5</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>x_[scope]_case_demo_10</sys_update_name>
        <type>Complaint</type>
    </x_[scope]_case>
</record_update>
